===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{senseid|en|lodging}} {{context|chiefly|British|usually|a mass noun|lang=en}} [[lodging|Lodging]] in a [[dwelling]] or similar living quarters afforded to travellers in hotels or on cruise ships, or prisoners, etc.
# {{context|countable|uncountable|followed by ''to''|lang=en}} The act of fitting or adapting, or the state of being fitted or adapted; adaptation; adjustment.
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|Sir Matthew Hale}}
#*: The organization of the body with '''accommodation''' to its functions.
# {{context|countable|uncountable|lang=en}} Willingness to accommodate; obligingness.
# {{context|countable|uncountable|lang=en}} Adjustment of differences; state of agreement; reconciliation; settlement; compromise.
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay}}
#*: To come to terms of '''accommodation'''.
# {{context|countable|lang=en}} The application of a writer's language, on the ground of analogy, to something not originally referred to or intended.
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|William Paley}}
#: Many of those quotations from the Old Testament were probably intended as nothing more than '''accommodations'''.
# {{context|countable|commerce|lang=en}} A loan of money.
# {{context|countable|commerce|lang=en}} An accommodation bill or note.
# {{context|countable|legal|lang=en}} An offer of [[substitute]] [[goods]] to [[fulfill]] a [[contract]], which will bind the [[purchaser]] if [[accepted]]
# {{context|countable|physiology|biology|lang=en}} The adaptation or adjustment of an organism, organ, or part.
# {{context|countable|medical|lang=en}} The adjustment of the eye to a change of the distance from an observed object.
# {{context|countable|geology|lang=en}} The place where sediments can make, or have made, a sedimentation.

